In '''2014 three shooting incidents occurred around Parliament Hill in Ottawa'''. The shootings began shortly before 10:00 [[UTC-4|EDT]] on October 22, 2014, when one gunman shot and killed a [[Canadian Forces]] soldier outside the [[National War Memorial (Canada)|Canadian National War Memorial]] where the soldier was on ceremonial guard duty. The gunman then proceeded into the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament buildings]], where he was reportedly shot dead by [[Kevin Vickers]], the [[List of Sergeants-at-Arms of the Canadian House of Commons|Sergeant-at-Arms of the Canadian House of Commons]].<ref name="CBC live">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/parliament-hill-attacked-soldier-shot-at-national-war-memorial-in-ottawa-1.2808710|title=Parliament Hill attacked, soldier shot at National War Memorial in Ottawa|date=22 October 2014|publisher=|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref><ref name="G&M breaking">{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/breaking-news-oct-22/article21217602/|title=Attack on Ottawa: Police in pursuit of multiple shooters|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref>

Subsequent to these initial events, Ottawa's downtown core was put under [[lockdown]], including Canada's Parliament and the [[University of Ottawa]].<ref name="CBC live" /><ref name="G&M breaking" /> The [[Ottawa Police Service]] stated they are investigating three shootings: one at the Canadian National War Memorial, one at [[Parliament Hill]], and one near the [[Rideau Centre]].<ref name="G&M breaking" /> The attack came a day after two Canadian Forces soldiers were struck by an [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] sympathizer in a car, killing one of them, and after Canada raised its terror threat level from low to medium.<ref name="BBC News">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-29724907?ns_mchannel=social&ns_campaign=bbc_breaking&ns_source=twitter&ns_linkname=news_central|title=Shots fired inside Canada parliament|work=BBC News|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref>

Earlier two men were seen jumping out of a Toyota Corolla and running toward the National War Memorial. The two gunmen then ran toward the [[Canadian Parliament]] building where 20-30 shots were fired. One gunmen was seen running with a double-barreled shotgun. One shooter was reportedly killed by security staff on [[Parliament Hill]].<ref>http://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/soldier-shot-at-war-memorial-in-ottawa</ref> The perpetrators were reported to be wearing scarfs around their heads and dressed in black. 

Ottawa Police also confirmed shots were fired near the Rideau Centre shopping mall just north of the War Memorial. Police retraced this statement later. The locations are all within a few hundred meters of each other. 

Ottawa hospitals reported receiving three shooting-related patients.

==Casualties==

The slain soldier was a reservist from Hamilton, Ontario and a member of the [[The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada (Princess Louise's)|Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders]]. He was on ceremonial guard duty at the Canadian National War Memorial which includes the tomb of the unknown soldier. He was taken to hospital but reported by Government Minister [[Jason Kenney]], CTV News, and CBC News as having died in hospital. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/hamilton/news/canadian-soldier-shot-in-ottawa-a-reservist-from-hamilton-1.2808960|title=Canadian soldier shot in Ottawa a reservist from Hamilton|date=22 October 2014|publisher=|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref>
	
A parliamentary guard was shot in the leg, and was treated in hospital for non-life threatening injuries. 

A third person was also shot, in an unspecified location. This person was taken to hospital with non-life threatening injuries.

